--- !u!114 &6359973630865846222
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 4740526428684312267}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Unity.TextMeshPro::TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "The Terracotta Female Nok sculpture is an iconic artifact created by the
    Nok culture, one of West Africa\u2019s earliest known civilizations, flourishing
    in present-day Nigeria between 1500 BCE and 500 CE. Made from fired clay, the
    sculpture reflects the Nok people\u2019s advanced artistic skill and early mastery
    of terracotta technology.\n\nFemale Nok figures often emphasize features such
    as elaborate hairstyles, triangular eyes, modeled jewelry, and intricate body
    decorations\u2014symbols believed to represent beauty, status, cultural identity,
    or spiritual power. The exaggerated facial details, including the characteristic
    pierced pupils and nostrils, are a hallmark of Nok artistry.\n\nThese sculptures
    are thought to play roles in ancient rituals, ancestral veneration, or fertility
    symbolism, although their exact use remains partly mysterious due to limited
    written records. Their discovery provides important evidence of complex social
    organization, early metallurgy, and long-distance trade networks in ancient West
    Africa.\n\nToday, Terracotta Nok sculptures are celebrated as some of the oldest
    known figurative artworks in Sub-Saharan Africa, offering invaluable insight
    into the creativity and worldview of an early African civilization."
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
