--- !u!114 &-2807142313068368073
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1673392923978847859}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: "The Terracotta Female Nok sculpture is an iconic artifact created
      by the Nok culture, one of West Africa\u2019s earliest known civilizations,
      flourishing in present-day Nigeria between 1500 BCE and 500 CE. Made from fired
      clay, the sculpture reflects the Nok people\u2019s advanced artistic skill
      and early mastery of terracotta technology.\n\nFemale Nok figures often emphasize
      features such as elaborate hairstyles, triangular eyes, modeled jewelry, and
      intricate body decorations\u2014symbols believed to represent beauty, status,
      cultural identity, or spiritual power. The exaggerated facial details, including
      the characteristic pierced pupils and nostrils, are a hallmark of Nok artistry.\n\nThese
      sculptures are thought to play roles in ancient rituals, ancestral veneration,
      or fertility symbolism, although their exact use remains partly mysterious
      due to limited written records. Their discovery provides important evidence
      of complex social organization, early metallurgy, and long-distance trade networks
      in ancient West Africa.\n\nToday, Terracotta Nok sculptures are celebrated
      as some of the oldest known figurative artworks in Sub-Saharan Africa, offering
      invaluable insight into the creativity and worldview of an early African civilization."
